<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-471-093  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 471 093.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Byte  Oct 1990 v15 n10 p368(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Spare me the details. (the computer user wants to get a job doneand not worry about how to use the computer)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Thompson, Tom.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Microcomputer users appreciate graphical user interfaces (GUIs)and other advances that enable users to be more productive without'mastering the peculiarities' of each application.andP;  Much remainsto be done, even well-designed GUIs (such as that of the AppleMacintosh computer) still require the user to be concerned aboutsuch details as the format of image files, whether a document istext-only, and filtering for various types of files.andP;  What isneeded is 'an interface where you type in plain questions and getreal answers.' Some of the processing power available with the newgenerations of 33MHz and faster microprocessors could be devotedto facilitating interfaces that handle all of the details ofcomputer operation, leaving the user to focus on their own work.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Graphical User InterfacePerformance ImprovementTransparencySystem designUser Needs.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>